name: isobutylbenzene
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The target compound, isobutylbenzene, is based on a benzene ring which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. The isobutyl group is an alkyl side chain which generally reduces the melting point of the benzene ring due to the branching making the molecule less symmetrical and pack less efficiently in a solid state. For a methyl group (-CH3), which is smaller, we would expect a decrease of about 10 degrees Celsius, however, for the isobutyl group which is larger and more branched (contains a secondary butyl structure), the effect would be greater. We might predict an additional decrease of around 30 to 40 degrees Celsius compared to benzene due to the isobutyl group. This is a rough estimate, as the precise effect of the alkyl group on the melting point will depend on its size and branching, but will generally follow the trend of causing a lower melting point as the size and branching increase.

name: isobutylbenzene

name: isobutylbenzene
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The target compound, isobutylbenzene, has benzene as its basic unit which has a melting point of 5.5°C. The presence of the isobutyl group (-(CH3)2CHCH2-) is expected to influence the melting point. The isobutyl group increases the molecular weight and provides some branching, which can lead to a decrease in the compactness of the molecular packing, possibly decreasing the melting point. Methyl groups on a benzene ring typically lower the melting point by around -5°C per methyl (observed by comparison to toluene). Since the isobutyl group has two methyl groups and extra methylene groups adding to the bulkiness, we can estimate a more substantial decrease. An approximate cumulative effect can be considered as -5°C for each methyl group and an additional decrease due to the extra methylene linkage and branching. Therefore, an estimated effect of the isobutyl group could be around -15°C to -20°C.

name: isobutylbenzene

Each methyl group in a molecule similar to toluene typically contributes a decrease of approximately -5°C to the melting point.
